<TEXT>
secretary of state james a baker iii banking 
on assurances from moscow says he expects ussoviet cooperation 
in foreign policy to stay on course after the departure of foreign 
minister eduard a shevardnadze 
baker at a news conference thursday said soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev sent reassurances that soviet foreign policy 
will not change as shevardnadze leaves 
since the united statessoviet partnership serves the interest 
of peace internationally and the process of reform domestically 
we of course expect that to be the case and we will be watching 
events closely in the weeks ahead baker said 
that means the bush administration intends to continue working 
with the soviets to reduce nuclear weapons stockpiles to try to 
end wars in afghanistan angola and cambodia and to force iraqs 
saddam hussein to reverse his annexation of kuwait 
however baker said shevardnadzes warning that rightwingers 
are pushing gorbachev toward dictatorship must be taken seriously 
the same critics who challenged gorbachev and shevardnadze on 
democratization at home also attacked their liberal policies in 
eastern europe and on german unification 
those policies were appreciated in washington and other western 
capitals west germany absorbed east germany once moscows closest 
ally and the unified country is in nato the other old soviet 
allies in eastern and central europe are groping toward democracy 
it was not clear whether shevardnadze resigned to try to stop 
the hardliners or whether he concluded that they had already 
succeeded in deflecting gorbachev from the path of reform and saw 
no point in staying 
only two weeks ago in houston baker advised shevardnadze that 
heavyhanded treatment of restive nationalities and economic 
profiteers could boomerang against the aid the administration had 
decided to give the soviets 
shevardnadzes credentials in the united states were not 
tarnished as gorbachev tried to cope with food shortages 
separatists in the baltics georgia and moldavia and with 
resistance from the right 
he has come across consistently as a truly committed 
democrat said a knowledgeable us official who requested 
anonymity he said perestroika economic reconstruction and 
democratization cannot be separated he was determined to remain 
true to that and he was careful not to attack gorbachev 
baker worked smoothly with shevardnadze appreciating his candor 
as well as his commitment to reform 
he was in the forefront of the new thinking in foreign policy 
and democratization at home baker said in a tribute and i 
think he that he has earned the respect of leaders all around the 
world 
together they put the finishing touches on a treaty to reduce 
nato and warsaw pact tanks and other nonnuclear weapons across the 
expanse of europe the accord was signed in paris last month 
they came close to agreement on a far more significant treaty to 
cut us and soviet longrange nuclear missiles bombers and 
submarines by about 30 percent overall president bush and 
gorbachev have scheduled a moscow summit feb 1113 to sign the 
pact after it is finished 
in the meantime the carefully coordinated squeeze play on iraq 
is entering a critical stage the un security council at the 
behest of the united states and with soviet support has set jan 15 
as the deadline for the withdrawal of all iraqi troops 
shevardnadze went along with the threat to use force with 
evident reluctance and the soviets are not contributing troops to 
any operation against iraq 
without soviet support the us campaign to reverse the august 
invasion would have run out of steam by now baker said thursday 
that he did not foresee any change 
president gorbachev himself has assured president bush on 
several occasions that the soviets do not intend to diverge from 
the united nations position on this issue baker said 
