<DOCNO> AP901221-0015 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the stunning resignation of foreign minister 
eduard shevardnadze seems aimed at revitalizing the flagging soviet 
reform movement and prodding mikhail gorbachev into quashing an 
upsurge by reactionaries 
democrats you have scattered shevardnadze told 
parliamentarians near the end of a rambling 15minute speech 
shevardnadze did not directly criticize gorbachev but he 
confronted him with a clear choice to preserve the fragile 
democratic institutions of perestroika or to risk crushing them by 
strengthening presidential powers to cope with the political and 
economic crisis 
shevardnadze along with gorbachev and alexander yakovlev was 
one of the three pillars of the perestroika reform movement and it 
was not clear whether the policy could stand on two legs at this 
moment of crisis 
gorbachev is asking the congress of peoples deputies to yet 
again strengthen the powers of his presidency hardliners are 
lobbying for him to declare a state of emergency and rule by decree 
in troubled regions particularly the three secessionist baltic 
republics 
shevardnadze noted in his speech that hardliners had succeeded 
in pressuring gorbachev to replace the moderate interior minister 
vadim bakatin with a kgb and an army general and said he thought 
he was their next target 
implicit in his speech was the idea that gorbachev has 
capitulated to the conservatives an idea that enunciated later by 
other reformers 
i think mr gorbachev should take mr shevardnadzes statement 
as a real signal that he is going too far to the right said 
moscow deputy mayor sergei stankevich 
i think gorbachev should make a crucial choice whether hes 
going to continue the course he started in launching the reforms 
in 1985 said stankevich 
the hardliners that shevardnadze accused of persecuting him 
gleefully welcomed his departure 
its a step in the right direction said col viktor 
alksnis a leader of the movement that has been urging gorbachev to 
declare a state of emergency and rule by presidential decree in 
tense areas of the country 
shevardnadze called gorbachev a friend and soulmate but his 
resignation recalled an earlier parting of the ways 
the resignation recalled the fiery speech delivered by another 
reformer boris n yeltsin at a closed party meeting in late 1987 
gorbachev drummed yeltsin out of the ruling politburo and now 
yeltsin stands as his most formidable political foe as president 
of the russian federation 
yeltsin in his speech said gorbachev was jeopardizing the 
reforms by not doing battle with hardliners a point very similar 
to shevardnadzes 
and yeltsin and shevardnadze also angered gorbachev by 
surprising him 
for me shevardnadzes announcement came as a surprise that 
more than anything else to tell the truth hurts me gorbachev 
told the congress picking his words carefully 
yakovlev pointedly made himself available to reporters in the 
cavernous white marble foyer of the kremlin palace of congresses 
he said he regretted shevardnadzes resignation but called the 
georgians prediction of dictatorship nonsense 
i wouldnt jump to such a conclusion he said but there 
are signs that the extreme right is raising its head and they have 
a glint in their eyes 
another gorbachev ally fyodor burlatsky appeared on the floor 
of the congress and asked the body to vote to request that 
shevardnadze remain as foreign minister it complied on a 154052 
vote but a shevardnadze spokesman said that the decision was 
irreversible 
 
editors note bryan brumley the associated press bureau chief 
in moscow has been covering soviet affairs since 1981 
</TEXT>
