<TEXT>
usx corp will pay a record 325 million fine 
to settle government allegations that it deliberately and 
repeatedly violated workersafety standards at two pennsylvania 
steel plants 
the settlement announced thursday stemmed from allegations 
leveled last year by the occupational safety and health 
administration the agency accused uss the steelmaking division of 
usx corp of more than 2000 federal job safety violations 
osha originally proposed a record 73 million fine for the 
violations which included hazards the government said were blamed 
for fatalities and not corrected the 325 million settlement is 
the largest workersafety fine to be collected eclipsing the 16 
million chrysler corp paid for violations at a plant in newark 
del 
the original osha citation charged that pittsburghbased usx 
permitted some of violations at the pennsylvania plants even 
though the company agreed two years ago to eliminate them at all 
its facilities 
in a statement the company said it agreed to pay the huge fine 
in part to avoid lengthy and costly legal battles over the 
governments allegations 
we continue to believe that both clairton works and fairless 
works are safe plants throughout our organization there is no 
higher priority than the safety and health of our people thomas 
w sterling vice president for employee relations at uss said in 
a statement 
clairton works near pittsburgh and fairless works near 
philadelphia were the two steel plants originally at issue in 
oshas complaint 
the united steelworkers of america the union representing about 
18000 usx workers cautioned against the significance of the 
settlement 
the agreement confirms the unions contentions that usx 
willfully allowed safety and health conditions in its facilities to 
deteriorate to such a point that workers were in serious danger 
a union statement said 
sterling said the company has already corrected several safety 
conditions at the two plants and other improvements were now being 
undertaken he said that during settlement negotiations with the 
government there had been many areas of substantial disagreement 
over the osha allegations 
the union said usx has refused to let the union review safety 
records or have an input on safety improvements 
this corporate attitude signals more battles over safety and 
health at a time when other steel companies have joined with the 
union in a variety of safetyrelated programs said andrew v 
lefty palm the unions chief negotiator in contract talks 
oshas original citation issued in november 1989 accused the 
company of failing to provide safe walking and working surfaces 
substandard cranesafety standards failure to properly guard 
machines and power transmission equipment noise violations 
failure to keep accurate records of injuries and illnesses 
structural flaws and violations of electricalsafety standards 
the citations stemmed from osha inspections that began earlier 
in 1989 following complaints from both the union and employees 
osha said three workers had died at the two plants in the two years 
leading up to the inspections there had been 17 such deaths since 
1972 
acting labor secretary roderick a dearment said all of usxs 
19000 workers would benefit from thursdays settlement because it 
calls for the company to take corporatewide action to strengthen 
safety and health protection 
gerard scannell an assistant secretary of labor who heads osha 
said the corporatewide safety programs will involve hearing 
conservation record keeping crane safety and hazard 
communications which involves employee training 
those programs will be implement at the two plants involved in 
the original complaint along with uss facilities in fairfield 
ala braddock pa dravosburg pa and chicago 
uss has also promised to meet with the state of indiana which 
operates its own oshaapproved occupational safety and health 
program to seek a similar agreement covering its gary ind 
works 
