<TEXT>
the federal government in one of the largest 
efforts of its kind is developing a threepronged effort to wipe 
out lead poisoning among children 
the initiative will involve removing leadbased paint from 
millions of homes with a focus on lowerincome families 
monitoring lead hazards in homes where children have high levels of 
lead in their blood and offering nutritional guidance as well as 
treatment are proposed and tighter drinking water standards and a 
ban on lead plumbing fixtures may be adopted 
this is saying we can eliminate this disease we dont need 
children being poisoned by lead in the united states said dr 
sue binder chief of the lead poisoning prevention branch in the 
centers for disease control 
the initiative will require close cooperation among all levels 
of government and the private sector 
it will require societywide effort binder said in an 
interview thursday 
the plans may be the largest effort designed to eliminate an 
environmental disease she said but so far the cdcs 
recommendations represent only a strategic plan we still need to 
think through the things we need to do and the details of how to do 
them she said 
cdcs plans are being circulated among top officials at the 
department of health and human services the environmental 
protection agency also has not announced its plans but the 
department of housing and urban development laid out its plans last 
week 
lead poisoning can damage the nervous system and lead to mental 
retardation and other mental disorders it also can damage the 
liver lead to paralysis of the arms and legs and cause 
convulsions the effects cannot be reversed 
children are most susceptible because their nervous systems are 
still developing and are sensitive to lead binder said their 
bodes also absorb more lead than adults do and they are exposed 
to higher levels of lead because they so often put things 
including dirty hands in their mouths she said 
the hud plan focuses on removing leadbased paint from homes or 
covering it over so it is no longer a health threat the plan 
includes a financial assistance program and is designed to help 
lowerincome families with children 
a hud study found that young children are living in about 38 
million us homes that have peeling leadbased paint or lead in 
household dust 
financial details of the plan will be disclosed as part of the 
federal budget for next fiscal year which begins oct 1 1991 
the health and human services plan is expected to be out in a 
few months binder said 
not all of the details of the plan have been worked out she 
said but it is based on an advisory committees recommendation for 
more aggressive monitoring testing and treatment 
current guidelines say steps ranging from nutritional 
education to medical treatment should be taken when lead in the 
blood reaches 25 micrograms per deciliter 
the advisory committee said intervention should begin when 
levels of 10 micrograms per deciliter are reached different levels 
of monitoring and testing were recommended for levels up to 25 
micrograms at which point medical treatment should be considered 
according to the committees guidance 
the committee is saying that environmental intervention 
nutritional information and education about lead poisoning need 
to start at lower levels of lead in the blood binder said 
an estimated 250000 children had lead levels above 25 
micrograms in 1984 she said 
the epa is considering tightening federal standards for lead in 
drinking water and prohibiting the use of lead in plumbing fixtures 
like brass faucets agency sources said a decision would be made 
early next year 
the epa also is considering banning the disposal of lead 
batteries in conventional garbage dumps 
</TEXT>
