mizraa looks like the ultimate 
kibbutz success story until you read the small print on the 
sausages liverwurst and frankfurters 
not of kosher type say the wrappers on many of the products 
that come out of mizraas meatprocessing plant its the 
kibbutzniks way of telling customers that the food contains pork 
now a law is before parliament that would outlaw the marketing 
of pork to the jewish public the result is an escalation of the 
long rancorous war between the secular public and the orthodox 
jewish parties which can make and break israeli governments 
orthodox jews revile pork as the most flagrantly nonkosher item 
on the list of edibles banned by biblical edict 
nonetheless it is widely available from butchers and 
restaurants which cater to the secular public but its a dish that 
dares not speak its name appearing instead under such euphemisms 
as special meat or white meat 
so why wait until now to take action we werent conscious 
until now of how much it was spreading says rabbi menachem 
porush whose agudat israel party is sponsoring the antipork law 
the truth is i dont even know what the thing looks like 
the ultramodern meat plant at mizraa in the jezreel valley in 
southern galilee earns 15 million a year 70 percent of the 
kibbutzs income 
mizraa doesnt breed pigs but it is israels largest source of 
nonkosher meat accounting for onefifth of the industry and 
exporting its delicacies all over the world 
it provides a living for thousands of people at the factory in 
the jezreel valley the pig farms owned by both jews and christians 
and mizraas nationwide chain of more than 300 delis 
moshe lapidot mizraas chief accountant says that beyond the 
money a principle is at stake 
we as secular free people living in a democratic country 
cant accept a small ultraorthodox minority trying to dictate 
fanatical religious laws whose time has passed he said over 
coffee in mizraas vast abundantly stocked deli 
the pig law is part of the religious legislation which prime 
minister yitzhak shamir promised as the price of adding agudat 
israels four parliamentary seats to his coalition 
but it has become a test case of how far the rabbis can enforce 
religious law 
already compromises are in the air agudat israel is now 
prepared to allow pork to be marketed in municipal districts with a 
christian population of more than 500 or 1000 
at first the religious camp refused to consider compensating 
those who stand to lose income rabbi avraham ravitz of the 
ultraorthodox torah flag party likens it to compensating pimps for 
income they would lose if prostitution were outlawed 
but this week the parliamentary committee was stopped in its 
tracks by a message from agriculture minister raphael eitan who 
insisted on discussing compensation 
shamir faces a tough choice the compensation bill could top 
500 million a fortune israel cannot afford but if the law is 
stalled he could lose agudat israels vital support 
the kibbutzniks are fighting back with demonstrations and bumper 
stickers 
three mizraa men were arrested recently on suspicion of burning 
tires in the orthodox town of bnei brak a protest tactic copied 
from palestinian activists in the occupied territories 
such incidents illustrate a widening rift between the 
kibbutzniks who regard themselves as the vanguard of secular 
zionism and the orthodox who regard themselves as defenders of 
the jewish heritage 
last march a prominent orthodox sage rabbi eliezer schach 
outraged the secular public by declaring there are kibbutzim 
that dont know what yom kippur is or the sabbath and they 
raise rabbits and pigs do they have any links with their 
forefathers 
yom kippur is the jewish day of atonement 
mizraa kibbutznik hadas sandorowicz says her own forefathers 
who helped build mizraa on jezreels swamps would be horrified to 
find the law being dictated by four nonzionist fanatics who 
didnt raise a finger to build this country 
