a federal judge has refused to delay 
implementation of a new ethics law that prohibits government 
workers from being paid for writing articles or making speeches 
us district judge thomas penfield jackson rejected the request 
for a temporary restraining order saying none of the employees had 
shown they would be irreparably harmed if they had to wait for 
the matter to be heard in court 
two public employees unions and the american civil liberties 
union representing 10 government workers filed suits to prevent 
enforcement of the ban on honoraria which takes effect jan 1 
jacksons refusal to delay implementation of the provision set 
the stage for the employees to file emergency appeals 
attorneys for the workers who earn outside income by lecturing 
writing freelance articles or performing religious ceremonies as 
ordaied clergy argued that the law unconstitutionally restricts 
freedom of speech 
justice department attorney jeffrey s gutman argued that the 
statute does not violate the first amendment because its only 
payment for speech that is prohibited by the statute not the 
speech itself 
gutman told jackson that the law may even apply to federal 
employees who are paid 50 a month to sing in their church choir 
he said however that the workers are free to continue their 
outside activities if the receive no compensation 
he noted that a 1974 law that has never been challenged in the 
courts prohibits federal employees from earning more than 2000 a 
year for articles speeches and appearances 
i find it startling this issue has not been litigated at 
all said jackson who did not rule on the merits of the issue 
lawyers for the national treasury employees union immediately 
filed a motion for a temporary emergency stay with the us court 
of appeals for the district of columbia 
attorneys for the american federation of government employees 
and the aclu which filed the companion cases said they would do 
the same as soon as possible 
the law was enacted in november 1989 as part of legislation that 
prohibited members of the house from receiving honoraria for 
speeches appearances and articles 
the ban does not apply to the senate but the office of 
government ethics says it is enforceable on virtually all federal 
employees with a possible civil fine of up to 10000 
