<TEXT>
a state agency wants to end the saga of the 
shoreham nuclear power plant by tearing down the idle reactor 
rather than mothballing or entombing it 
the long island power authority has asked its board of trustees 
to approve a plan to dismantle and decontaminate the reactor at a 
cost of 186 million the authority hopes to ship the reactors 
radioactive parts out of state to a certified nuclear waste dump 
the authority rejected two more costly options mothballing in 
which the plant would be shut down for 20 or 30 years but could be 
started up again and entombment burying the plant inside a wall 
the authoritys trustees were to vote on the plan today if 
approved it will be submitted to the federal nuclear regulatory 
commission before the end of the year authority chairman richard 
kessel said at a news conference thursday 
the 55 billion shoreham plant on the north shore of long 
island about 60 miles east of new york city was completed in 1984 
after 11 years of construction it received a full operating 
license from the nrc but only was tested at 5 percent of capacity 
and never generated electricity 
gov mario cuomo and suffolk county officials opposed the plant 
arguing that long island could not be safely evacuated if a nuclear 
accident occurred 
in 1987 shoreham owner long island lighting co agreed to sell 
the plant to the state for 1 in return for annual rate increases 
for 10 years the power authority is overseeing the shutdown 
kessel also executive director of the state consumer protection 
board said that if the nrc accepts the decommissioning plan within 
the next nine months the power authority could start dismantling 
the reactor in october and finish in late 1993 
the nrc has not yet ruled on an application filed last june to 
transfer shorehams operating license from long island lighting to 
the power authority the commission is waiting for the authority to 
decide which decommissioning plan to pursue 
