<TEXT>
a retired air force official said cargo jets 
used extensively in operation desert shield in saudi arabia have 
not been thoroughly inspected a newspaper reported today 
retired lt col lawrence b welborn told the los angeles times 
that the air force only looked at a fraction of the lockheed c5b 
aircraft frames they later told congress they tested for defects 
a lockheed spokesman said the plane does not have structural 
flaws but said he was unfamiliar with the details of the air 
forces inspections 
the tests previously performed by lockheed and validated by 
the air force metallurgists established the metallurgical soundness 
of the c5bs the spokesman said 
welborn said he was in charge of the inspections in 1986 at 
altus air force base in oklahoma in a sworn affidavit and in an 
interview with the newspaper welborn said that only one area of 
one c5bs frame was exposed for testing on dec 6 1986 three 
c5bs were supposed to be tested 
the test he said only took a few hours to fully test the 
entire structure of the three planes would have taken several days 
he said 
welborns affidavit taken by claremont calif attorney 
herbert hafif was received by rep john d dingell dmich who 
was on the oversight and investigations subcommittee that requested 
the 1986 inspections 
dingell demanded thursday that the defense department 
investigate whether the air force misled congress 
possible structural flaws were brought to the attention of 
congress in 1986 by three former lockheed employees represented by 
hafif 
those employees claimed that because of a defective oven the 
jets mainframes were overheated causing cracks and voids in the 
metal 
after congress request for the inspection in 1986 gen 
lawrence skantze then the air forces procurement chief reported 
to the committee that the structural integrity of the 24 
suspected forgings was confirmed diagrams of the test points 
were presented to the committee 
but on thursday skantze said he had no firsthand knowledge of 
the inspections but was assured at the time that the inspection had 
been completed 
given the gravity of the issue i am appalled that our people 
would have assured me the job was done correctly if indeed it was 
not done he told the times 
last month a los angeles jury awarded the employees a 453 
million award in a civil case claiming they were fired after trying 
