<TEXT>
suez canal authorities have stepped up 
security against a possible iraqi attempt to scuttle a vessel in 
the waterway to block it canal officials said today 
the measures include assigning cement carriers to the rear of 
canal convoys so that if they are sunk other vessels would not be 
blocked once sunk cement carriers are extremely difficult to 
clear because of the wet cement 
the canal is important for oil shipping as well as for the 
united states and other countries massing warships in the persian 
gulf region 
because the canal carries much of western europes oil an 
extended blockage would hit that regions economy hard and could be 
almost ruinous to egypts the canal annually earns more than 15 
billion in foreign exchange for egypt 
canal security has been tighter since egypt condemned iraqs 
aug 2 invasion of kuwait and sent troops to join the usled 
multinational force deployed in the gulf region to defend against 
further iraqi advances 
intelligence sources in cairo said today the new canal measures 
were in line with a security upgrade ordered nationwide on 
strategic installations like the canal the aswan high dam in 
southern egypt and vital industries 
canal officials said authorities recently began careful checks 
of the itineraries and ownership of cementcarrying ships 
particularly those coming from the far east or the gulf region 
today a romanian ship carrying cement the 38000ton beius 
was the last of 30 ships to transit the 101mile long canal it 
origin and destination were unclear 
the canal officials speaking on condition of anonymity said 
the suez canal authority took the additional safeguard of 
dispatching two tugboats to follow the romanian ship through the 
waterway 
they said more egyptian harbor workers and stevedores than usual 
have been boarding all cementcarrying ships such workers provide 
dockside and harbor services at the southern and northern ends of 
the canal suez and port said 
in addition they report to egyptian intelligence on anything 
unusual found aboard ships 
as a rule suez canal authority pilots steer ships through the 
waterway 
despite its value to egypt president gamal abdel nasser in 1956 
scuttled two ships carrying concrete and stones in the waterway to 
block it he aimed to hurt western economies in reprisal for a 
concerted military attack on egypt by britain france and israel 
iraqi president saddam hussein threatened in august to punish 
arab states that sided with kuwait in the crisis recently 
proiraqi palestinian hardliner mohammed abbas extended the threat 
to the united states and kuwaits other western allies 
