<TEXT>
new yorks highest court has granted 
workers compensation benefits to a school bus driver who suffered 
severe psychological problems after seeing the wreckage of a fatal 
car crash 
the state court of appeals awarded the benefits thursday to rose 
wood who was driving a busload of kindergartners to school on 
april 29 1986 when she came upon a car accident in which two 
teenagers she knew were killed 
in its 70 decision the court said psychological pain brought 
on by witnessing a tragedy can be considered an accidental injury 
and can be subject to the same compensation as a physical injury 
the court said however that compensation isnt necessarily due 
all employees who suffer mental pain after seeing an injury to 
someone else at work 
what the court seems to be saying is that the closer you are 
to being an active participant the more likelihood you have of 
winning the case said thomas dunne lawyer for the workers 
compensation board 
wood then 50 was the first person on the accident scene and 
saw the mangled body of one of the victims the court said wood 
remained at the scene until emergency help arrived and then 
continued on her route the court said 
within weeks of the accident wood began suffering from 
insomnia nightmares anorexia depression and chest pains the 
court said less than two months after the accident wood was 
involved in a nearcollision between her school bus again filled 
with kindergarten children and an automobile 
wood then was hospitalized and treated for stress the court 
said wood of coxsackie about 25 miles south of albany couldnt 
return to the job shed held for 12 years she has been out of work 
since and remains under treatment said her lawyer brendan quinn 
wood then sought workers compensation benefits from her 
employer laidlaw transit an administrative law judge for new 
yorks workers compensation board rejected woods claim to 
compensation for lost wages but the full compensation board 
overturned that decision and awarded benefits 
the bus company took the case to the appellate division of state 
supreme court which dismissed the award that court said that 
while woods disability arose in the course of her job she 
technically was not involved in an accident 
the court of appeals however said there was no question that 
woods psychological and emotional problems were a direct result of 
her job judge judith kaye said that wood as a school bus driver 
had job responsibilities that distinguished her from others who 
might have passed on the road 
rose wood was by virtue of her employment an active 
participant more than a third party merely witnessing anothers 
injury kaye said the feeling on woods part that she should 
have been able to help but couldnt precipitated her 
psychological injuries 
its now up to the compensation board to determine how much wood 
can receive in benefits quinn said if shes granted full 
disability she can be compensated at twothirds of her salary for 
the 4 years since the accident about 45000 quinn said 
the lawyer for laidlaw transit leo hacker did not return 
telephone calls to his office thursday or early today 
</TEXT>
