<TEXT>
four leading western economic institutions 
said today that soviet president mikhail gorbachev must accelerate 
the pace of reform in his country or run the risk that the effort 
could fail 
the longawaited study the most comprehensive look yet by the 
west at the crumbling soviet economy called for economic pain in 
the form of wage controls imposed on workers at the same time price 
controls are removed from a variety of goods 
it said such bitter medicine was the only way to stabilize the 
chaotic situation in the soviet union where consumers in major 
cities are faced with massive shortages of food and other essential 
products 
the authorities face an enormous task involving reforms of 
the legal financial and trade systems and also of vital sectors of 
the economy especially agriculture distribution energy and 
manufacturing said the report it was prepared by the 
international monetary fund with help from three other 
organizations 
these changes cannot be made in a matter of weeks the study 
concluded but the imperative is to make sufficient progress at 
the beginning so that reform is seen as an irreversible break with 
the past and the process gains an unstoppable momentum 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the western experts conceded that the plan they were putting 
forward could not be implemented without economic pain but said 
they knew of no other way to transform the soviet system 
ideally a path of gradual reform could be laid out which 
would minimize economic disturbance and lead to an early harvesting 
of the fruits of increased economic efficiency the study said 
but we know of no such path the more particularly given the 
difficult starting conditions 
but the study said that gorbachev had passed the point of no 
return in his efforts saying it would probably be impossible to 
reinstitute a centrally planned economy even if he wanted to 
therefore the experts urged the soviet leaders to move 
rapidly to give substance to their commitment to a market 
economy 
while calling for technical assistance to help the soviets in 
their efforts to discard seven decades of a planned economy the 
study said that massive amounts of western aid would not be useful 
right now 
it said that without the implementation of a major and 
farreaching reform program direct western aid would be of 
little or no lasting value 
the 50page report represented a victory for the bush 
administration which has argued for months that massive amounts of 
western aid would be wasted until gorbachev made more extensive 
moves to reform his economy 
however it cited certain specific areas where western technical 
expertise and investment could be of value 
immediate new investment could have a quick payoff for the 
ussr and the rest of the world in the energy and environment 
sectors the report said 
it cited modernization of nuclear plants improvement of oil 
drilling technologies and updating the soviets gas pipeline 
systems as projects where foreign investment would be most useful 
in the short term 
foreign assistance also could be particularly useful in 
retailing and distribution two areas that will be critical in the 
transition to a market economy the report said 
the united states and other countries already have dispatched 
experts to help the soviets remove the bottlenecks in their 
crumbling distribution system 
in addition to the imf other groups participating in the study 
were the world bank and two europeanbased economic agencies the 
organization for economic cooperation and development and the 
european bank for reconstruction and development 
president bush met with imf director michel camdessus and world 
bank president barber conable on thursday to discuss the report 
which was ordered up by bush and other leaders at the sevennation 
economic summit last july in houston 
the study represented a compromise last summer between demands 
by the french and germans for an immediate 15 billion western aid 
package and resistance to direct economic aid by bush and the other 
summit leaders 
todays report however indicated that no large sums of public 
money were called for in the current period instead it said a 
large part of this technical assistance should be provided by the 
private sectors of western countries with the role of public 
sectors being limited to filling any important gaps 
due to the breakdown of the distribution system food shortages 
are appearing in moscow leningrad and other major soviet cities 
particularly those farthest from agricultural regions germany and 
a number of other european countries have embarked on food relief 
programs for the soviet union 
the united states has offered the soviets 1 billion in bank 
guarantees to help them buy us grain and is coordinating a 
program to encourage the private sector to supply medical supplies 
and drugs to relieve shortages 
food aid if targeted and successfully delivered to the 
regions most affected could alleviate present distress the 
study said but it added an early implementation of economic 
reform would make the single largest contribution to alleviation of 
shortages 
the report which took five months to prepare portrayed a 
system that was even more backward than expected and practically 
paralyzed in its stumbling efforts to implement gorbachevs 
restructuring program 
inflation is accelerating at a pace that is difficult to 
measure with the old centralized order being replaced by a chaotic 
system of bartering and black marketeering it said 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said the administration 
did not believe the surprise resignation thursday of soviet foreign 
minister eduard a shevardnadze would derail the efforts to get 
western technical assistance to the soviet economy 
he said the united states would discuss the report with other 
summit countries germany japan britain france italy and 
canada in order to coordinate efforts finance ministers and 
central bank presidents of the seven nations are expected to meet 
in washington in late january 
in addition to the 1 billion in food credits the 
administration also announced last week that it supports a move to 
make the soviet union a special associate of the imf and the 
world bank that would qualify the country for technical help but 
no direct loans from the two lending organizations 
</TEXT>
