<TEXT>
three indigent people have sued los angeles 
county saying the countys relief payments are insufficient to 
ward off hunger and homelessness 
the lawsuit against the county board of supervisors claims that 
the maximum payment of 312 a month established after another 
lawsuit is grossly inadequate to feed clothe and shelter the 
indigent 
the allotment allows 200 a month for housing 95 for food and 
17 for transportation personal needs and clothing according to 
the lawsuit filed thursday in los angeles county superior court 
the suit asks that the board be ordered to immediately raise 
the monthly grant amounts by amounts sufficient to enable indigent 
recipients to meet their basic subsistence needs 
it does not specify how much money that is 
the general relief program is the final safety net for aid and 
assistance to many destitute people said the plaintiffs lawyer 
john brinsley this monthly allocation has not been increased 
since mid1988 and is significantly below the federal poverty 
line 
the county continues to be the provider of last resort said 
deputy county counsel patrick wu wu said he had not seen the 
lawsuit and could not comment further on it 
brinsley said the supervisors ignored an increase recommended by 
their own elfare director and chief administrative officer voting 
to keep payments the same 
those representing the plaintiffs in the classaction suit 
include the legal aid foundation of los angeles the inner city law 
center and western center on law and poverty inc 
three relief recipients elizabeth mendly rudy johnson and 
john butts jr are named as plaintiffs but the suit specifies 
that plaintiffs bring this action on behalf of themselves and all 
