<TEXT>
the world bank said friday it no longer was 
counting on payments from iraq and was starting to put aside 
reserves to cover 514 million owed by iraq 
the bank owned by 154 countries including iraq lends about 21 
billion a year and is the biggest single source of aid to the third 
world the united states holds the largest block of shares 
iraqs foreign debt totalled 237 billion last year according 
to the central intelligence agency despite its wealth from oil 
iraq borrowed heavily because of its long war with iran 
the banks decision effective last monday was announced 
friday it put iraq on nonaccrual status normal practice when 
a country is six months behind on its payments it means that 
payments from the debtor country are no longer listed on the banks 
books since payments have not actually arrived 
there are 102 million in payments overdue from iraq 71 
million principal and 31 million interest 
the bank also will put aside 1 percent of the debt each month as 
a reserve in case it is never repaid 
other countries froze iraqs assets following its aug 2 
invasion of kuwait as a result president saddam husseins 
government has been unable to make payments the bank said in a 
statement after 75 days of not paying iraq lost the right to new 
loans from the bank 
eight other countries are also on nonaccrual status because 
they have been unwilling or unable to pay syria liberia zambia 
somalia peru panama nicaragua and guatemala two others guyana 
and honduras have paid up and returned to normal status so that 
they are once again entitled to borrow from the bank 
