<TEXT>
the food and drug administration on friday 
approved a new genetically engineered drug to treat a rare 
lifethreatening immune disorder that strikes mostly boys 
people with chronic granulomatous disease or cgd are missing a 
key element of the immune system leaving them susceptible to 
bacterial and fungal infections and reliant on high doses of 
antibiotics 
the fda said the new therapy is the first approved genetically 
engineered form of gamma interferon a naturally occurring 
infectionfighting protein produced by certain types of white blood 
cells 
genentech inc of south san francisco calif will market the 
drug under the brand name actimmune 
the drug needs to be injected only three times a week in most 
cases which means we can now expect patients to have a more 
normal daytoday life said dr louis sullivan secretary of the 
department of health and human services which includes the fda 
fewer than 400 americans have cgd federal health officials 
said because it is so rare the drug was developed under the fdas 
orphan drug program designed to encourage development of drugs 
to treat rare diseases 
about 80 percent of children with the disorder suffer unusually 
frequent or severe infections within their first two years of life 
sometimes these infections can retard normal growth or lead to 
death the fda said 
common side effects of the drug include headache fever rashes 
and chills but these were transient the fda said 
longterm effects of the drug are not known but will be 
evaluated in postmarketing studies the fda said 
however because the drug has been shown to cause miscarriages 
in animals the fda said it should not be used during pregnancy 
unless its benefits clearly outweigh the potential risks 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

