<TEXT>
the federal election commission voted 
unanimously to dismiss allegations that proisrael lobbying groups 
broke election laws by illegally coordinating their activities 
according to documents released friday 
the commission said its six members find no reason to 
believe the american israel public affairs committee aipac 
violated lobbying rules in connection with 27 political action 
committees around the country 
the vote was taken last year but was kept secret because an 
unrelated complaint involving aipac and other organizations is 
still pending said commission spokesman fred eiland 
the agency disclosed its findings only after lengthy arguments 
with the complainants who requested publication of the material 
under the freedom of information act 
the complaint filed jan 12 1989 was brought by several 
former us officials who have long argued that aipac exercises 
undue influence on congress and skews us foreign policy in 
israels favor 
they accused aipac of failing to disclose what they said was its 
coordination of the 27 other pacs 
in the undecided case the same plaintiffs contended aipac 
should have registered as a political action committee because 
they said it targeted political candidates for election or defeat 
based on their position toward israel this case involves the 
alleged use of a black book containing vital information on 
every senate and house race 
aipac responded that such activities were internal 
communications with its 55000 members and protected by supreme 
court rulings 
in the case that it decided the fec said there was not enough 
evidence to show that aipac and the other proisrael committees 
were affiliated 
although the 27 pacs received information regarding 
congressional races it appears that each respondent pac makes 
independent decisions regarding which candidates to support the 
commission said 
the plaintiffs demanded that aipac be forced to register as a 
public action committee and disclose its activities a move that 
would have hampered behindthescenes lobbying with congress and 
the administration 
among the plaintiffs were onetime ambassador to saudi arabia 
james e akins paul findley who says he lost his seat in congress 
in 1982 because of an aipac campaign and george ball who served 
as undersecretary of state in the kennedy and johnson 
administrations 
the complaint relied on large measure on news reports about the 
activities of the lobbying group in addition to two internal aipac 
memoranda 
aipacs 125page response accompanied by hundreds of pages of 
exhibits said no one directs american jews to become active in 
liberal organizations or conservative organizations or in 
political campaigns or to give to candidates or to form political 
organizations of their own 
the fec found that the similar pattern of political 
contributions by the 27 pacs resulted from their focus on 
candidates who support israel and did not reflect collusion between 
them and aipac 
