<TEXT>
in a rare mood southern californians 
praised a freeway instead of cursing it as the granddaddy of 
freeways celebrated its 50th birthday friday 
though the 82mile pasadena freeway the first in the west 
looks like a museum piece the sunken sixlane freeway is among the 
states safest despite thrillride curves and floorit 
suddenstop ramps 
the first fivemile section of the freeway opened dec 30 1940 
in a small park beside one especially harrowing curve the 
california department of transportation celebrated the anniversary 
with a sign denoting the spans significance 
almost predictably the celebrations marching band caused some 
passing motorists to swerve in the narrowgauge lanes 
joining the festivities were descendants of construction crew 
members and the gabrielino indians who transferred the land to the 
state in a 1940 ceremony public officials and the university of 
southern california marching band 
sally stanton rubsamen the 1940 rose queen who dedicated the 
ribbon of concrete a halfcentury ago recalled trips to school 
using successively longer parts of the newly completed surface 
it was a freeway then she said 
adding that she now commutes daily from pasadena to los angeles 
rubsamen said the lanes are a bit narrow its a little curvy 
its beautiful but some of the on ramps and off ramps are 
atrocious 
nearly 130000 cars a day roll over the pasadena freeway which 
meanders from downtown los angeles to pasadena through the arroyo 
seco the dry gulch was surveyed but not used for a road in 1895 
when first proposed the freeways promise was pasadena to downtown 
in 10 minutes some trips now take more than an hour 
although roads called parkways were already built in the east 
and the autobahn was about to cross germany no one new what to 
call what was then billed as the cutting edge of transportation 
development 
stopless motorway was one suggestion 
it was built in 33 months at a cost of 1 millionplus a mile 
freeways today cost 100 million per mile it was originally 
designed for travel at 45 mph without traffic some commuters whip 
around its curves at 70 
it was the new thing in transportation engineering said 
alfred himelhoch an engineer on the project we didnt know too 
much about it because we were on the cutting edge 
himelhoch who has since worked on nearly every freeway in the 
los angeles area recalled the trepidation of starting work on the 
new project 
its scary to work on any freeway he said 
public reaction to the project was not divided by the protests 
surrounding modern freeway construction he added it was a new 
venture and people didnt know as much about a freeway the 
discussion as to merit and impact on the community came later 
himelhoch said each lane is 10 or 11 feet wide falling short of 
todays 12foot standard motorists sometimes have 10 feet to 
accelerate to 55 miles per hour and some exits require cars to 
slow to 5 mph while still in the slow lane 
but himelhoch said safety was the main goal of any freeway more 
important than moving people 
freeways are three times as safe as surface roads because of 
the divider between directions and the ramps which bring cars 
smoothly onto them he said 
the pasadena freeways safety rate is 184 reportable accidents 
for every million vehicle miles traveled one of californias best 
state officials said 
the los angeles freeway system contains 4 percent of the surface 
area of californias roads but carries more than 40 percent of the 
states traffic 
though celebrating the route that paved the way for 4047 miles 
of future freeways officials friday hinted at the end of the 
freeway age 
fifty years ago this magnificent and ambitious project was the 
answer to the transit needs of a growing and increasingly mobile 
population said state sen art torres but today our needs are 
drastically increased and the demands of the environment must 
force us to look beyond 
torres advocated a light rail system and a proposed monorail 
that would run 58 miles along the los angeles river to long beach 
perhaps more freeways are not the answer torres said 
