the securities and exchange commission filed 
civil fraud charges friday against the bankrupt latin investment 
corp an uninsured storefront bank whose collapse threw more 
than 68 million in deposits into jeopardy 
the sec lawsuit filed in federal court in washington also 
sought a court order freezing the assets of three top officers of 
latin investment corp which catered primarily to latin american 
immigrants 
the washingtonbased corporations assets were frozen dec 15 
when it was forced into involuntary bankruptcy 
the sec said it had contacted the government of el salvador to 
locate any assets there that would be subject to a freeze order 
also named in the lawsuit were lic founder fernando leonzo of 
vienna va the corporations secretary leonel salinas of falls 
church va and vice president jose a cortes of arlington va 
the three men also sit on the board of el latino a weekly 
hispanic newspaper and lic subsidiary 
the secs civil complaint was filed just three days after leonzo 
invoked his fifth amendment rights against self incrimination and 
refused to answer questions under oath according to documents 
filed by the agency 
many of the investors put much of their life savings in lic 
relying on materially false and misleading representations of lic 
leonzo salinas and cortes the complaint charged 
according to the complaint lic founded in 1982 had about 
3500 investors who had placed about 68 million with the 
investment company as of august 1990 
but the wilson international center a private community group 
that is helping victims of lics collapse said the amount in 
jeopardy was more like 13 million in deposits an average of more 
than 3700 apiece 
the sec lawsuit sought a court order requiring full restitution 
to investors who were defrauded 
the lawsuit also sought a restraining order to keep the three 
officers from destroying any documents or transferring assets 
the complaint alleges that lic which operated without a bank 
charter or government banking insurance misled investors into 
thinking their funds would be safe and available on demand 
the sec also alleged that the three officers did not disclose to 
investors that they received more than 500000 in loans some of 
which was used to pay for their homes from the investment company 
as of august none of those loans had been repaid the sec said 
leonzo through his lawyer charles pearson denied the sec 
allegations 
we have a different version of events and that will certainly 
come forward in due time pearson said were not trying to 
hide anything what were trying to do is repay depositors 
last week a federal bankruptcy judge ordered without 
opposition from leonzo that the company be liquidated 
