ranchers broke up ice in cattle troughs and 
workers stayed busy repairing brittle rail telephone and plumbing 
lines as record low temperatures gripped northern and central 
nevada on friday 
the arctic storm that chilled western states most of the week 
pushed temperatures in reno to minus 7 snapping a 22year record 
of 3 degrees below zero 
pretty near froze to death out there this morning said bob 
wallis who works at the blue diamond ranch in eureka where 
fridays low plunged to minus 12 degrees 
even after 40 years of range roaming you never get used to 
that wallis said 
wallis said that despite the cold the cowboys at the 6000head 
ranch were checking the cattles health each day 
they get pneumonia and stuff when it gets this cold and we go 
out and doctor them he said thats all i do is doctor 
others were keeping the herd stocked with fodder and breaking up 
icebergs that formed in water troughs he said 
in reno even thickfurred malamute dogs balked at going 
outside 
plumbers reported a brisk business 
were all booked up said a dispatcher at abc plumbing 
the phones started ringing at 4 am and were still getting 
them 
while plumbers scrounged around in flooded basements the cold 
slowed down telephone workers installing lines for special 
teenager gab phones that parents had ordered for christmas 
being as cold as it is nothing works said kelly sanford of 
nevada bell everything is just nearly frozen your nose freezes 
