<TEXT>
the army and the navy said friday the past 
year was their safest on record private vehicle accidents remained 
the biggest killer of soldiers and sailors 
the army said 353 servicemen and women were killed in accidents 
during the budget year ended sept 30 including those that 
occurred offbase and offduty 
the time period included the first rush of troops to the persian 
gulf 
more than twothirds of the deaths were from private automobile 
accidents in the comparable period a year earlier the army had 
369 accidental deaths 
there were 732000 army personnel on active duty at the end of 
accounting period 
total army accidents were down by 1348 from the previous year 
to 8647 and deaths from aviation accidents fell from 35 to 33 
col steven raho deputy director of army safety attributed the 
safety improvement to a variety of factors including increased 
effort by the army to design safety features into new equipment 
rather than adding the features after production 
the navy which had 579000 personnel on active duty at the end 
of the budget year said it recorded 255 total deaths from 
accidents including 206 not related to navy operations that was 
down from 339 total navy deaths the year before of which 47 
occurred in the april 19 1989 explosion aboard the battleship uss 
iowa 
twothirds of total navy accidental deaths were from private 
vehicle wrecks 
the navy had 39 deaths from aviation accidents including those 
involving marine corps aircraft the navy total of 30 deaths from 
aviation was the lowest on record as was the marine corps total of 
nine 
the marines do not publish lists of accidents from ground 
activities and the air force said it was not yet prepared to 
release its statistics on fiscal 1990 accidents and deaths 
