the decision to excise stalin from public life came on what 
would have been the soviet dictators 111th birthday authorities 
also ordered the renaming of all streets institutions and even a 
city named after stalin 
albania became the last eastern european state to reject the 
symbols of stalinism the communist leadership made the decision 
taking into consideration that historic circumstances have 
changed the state news agency ata said 
before the order was issued friday workers already had removed 
the imposing bronze statue of the dictator that had stared down at 
tirana residents since before his death in 1953 
clusters of tirana residents watched all morning as workers 
finished the job dismantling the marblecovered pedestal from its 
place in a central park another giant statue was toppled at a 
textile works in tirana overnight 
fridays decison announced by ata called for the renaming of 
qyteti stalin the last city in europe named after stalin 
also friday the albanian leadership gave its permission for a 
rally by the new opposition democratic party on saturday according 
to opposition sources it would be the first legal opposiiton rally 
in albania since the communists took power in 1944 
several thousand students rallied in tirana last week to demand 
democratic change and to hail the founding of the first 
noncommunist party police did not intervene 
the significance of stalins demise was not lost on albanians 
who were repressed for decades by the ironfisted rule of enver 
hoxha the albanian communist who adored stalin 
the change should have happened a long time ago said an 
albanian journalist on condition of anonymity 
it is not clear however just how far albanian leaders are 
willing to go toward creating a true democracy 
albanias nascent opposition has encountered numerous obstacles 
most of all the ruling party opposition leaders say local 
communist officials still hinder party activists travelling to 
provincial cities 
there is also entrenched support for the communists in the 
media with few details on the newly recognized democratic party 
appearing in news reports 
and the ruling communists are playing tough cracking down on 
riots in four cities last week with a massive show of army and 
police force and handing out tough sentences of up to 20 years to 
those arrested 
tirana was the last capital in europe to boast a monument to the 
soviet dictator whose personality cult led to the murder of 
millions on the continent 
now lets take down the statue of the dictator who ruled here 
for 50 years said one bold youth watching the workers friday 
he was referring to a giant statue of hoxha that dominates the 
nearby central square 
dismantling hoxhas legacy will prove complicated although he 
has been held responsible for cruel repression in the 1950s and the 
isolationist policy that has brought albanias economy close to 
collapse hoxha achieved national unity and independence for 
virtually the first time in the balkan nations turbulent history 
his name is emblazoned on buildings streets and memorials 
throughout albania and his books and portraits adorn every 
institution 
yet president ramiz alia who took over after hoxha died in 
1985 appears to be pushing his reforms through despite the 
presence of hardliners in the secretive ruling elite 
the end of stalins cult came one day after hoxhas 71yearold 
widow nexhmije hoxha lost her last political post as head of the 
communistled democratic front officially retiring because of old 
age 
she was replaced by premier adil carcani who is in his late 
60s rumors persist that carcani will step down soon as head of 
government 
the communists promised a government change when they bowed 
earlier this month to demands for more democracy but so far no 
changes have been announced 
a party conference dec 26 is expected to give some indication 
of the partys new policies it is supposed to decide a program for 
elections scheduled for feb 10 in which the communists will face 
opposition for the first time since taking power in 1944 
the newly founded democratic party is pushing for postponement 
of the elections arguing it has insufficient time to organize 
to date the media have reported no details of the new partys 
program the party is also negotiating with the government to 
publish its own daily newspaper 
</TEXT>
