the federal reserve set the stage for its 
recent interest rate reductions at a midnovember meeting of its 
monetary policy committee according to minutes of the meeting 
released friday 
the central bank has permitted a lowering of its federal funds 
rate four times since october and on wednesday dropped the discount 
rate from 7 percent to 65 percent the first decline in four 
years 
the 025 percentage point decline in the federal funds rate on 
oct 29 to 775 percent was in response to the federal 
budgetcutting agreement between the bush adminsitration and 
congress 
but the federal open market committee noted weakening economic 
activity at its nov 13 meeting and agreed to another slight 
reduction 
the move the minutes said was designed to provide some 
insurance against a deep and prolonged recession without incurring 
a substantial risk in current circumstances of fostering 
intensified inflationary pressures 
and the minutes said the committee agreed to give weight to 
potential developments that might require some slight further 
easing until the next meeting which was held last tuesday and was 
followed by the discount rate reduction and the lowering of the 
federal funds rate to 70 percent 
between the two meetings the federal funds rate fell to 75 
percent on nov 16 and to 725 percent on dec 7 the rate is the 
interest banks charge each other for overnight loans the discount 
rate is the interest the fed charges banks 
the minutes show that the committee members were concerned about 
the growing signs of a softening economy the related 
vulnerability of many business and financial firms to added 
financial strains and the increased reluctance of institutional 
lenders to accommodate less than prime business borrowers 
the committee vote was unanimous the feds monetary 
policysetting arm is comprised of the seven board members and five 
of the 12 presidents of the feds regional banks there currently 
is one vacancy on the board 
