<TEXT>
winter made its entrance friday on howling frigid winds 
generated by an arctic cold front 
on the first official day of winter the cold front ushered snow 
and bitter cold temperatures into the mississippi valley and the 
southern plains temperatures plunged below zero from the northern 
plateau and the great basin to the upper mississippi valley 
turning gasoline to gel and stranding motorists by the hundreds 
three cities reported alltime record lows friday morning 
casper wyo hit 41 below zero redding calif dropped to 17 to 
tie their record and sacremento matched its all time low of 21 
degrees 
amtraks empire builder from seattle to chicago was delayed 
by the cold the train that left seattle on tuesday arrived in 
fargo nd 24 hours late 
its cold enough to crack rails when the ice builds up 
amtrak spokesman john jacobsen said sometimes it just separates 
the rails but whether it actually cracks a rail or simply 
separates a rail you cant operate a train you have to wait to 
get a repair crew there 
as the cold moved south the temperature dropped 24 degrees in 
30 minutes in page okla a small town in the ouachita national 
forest it was 2 below in amarillo texas and 6 above in lubbock 
snow extended across much of the great plains at midday 
spreading into the middle and upper mississippi valley strong 
northwesterly winds brought bitter arctic air into the center of 
the nation resulting in dangerous wind chill factors 
jamestown nd reported a wind chill of 70 below zero while 
winds at grand forks produced a wind chill of 76 degrees below 
zero 
winter storm warnings watches and advisories were posted into 
saturday from the northern plains to the southern plains and the 
mississippi valley for heavy snow and debilitating wind chills 
friday mornings low for the lower 48 states was 50 below zero 
at worland wyo 
