<TEXT>
the coal industry always battered by 
economic and labor uncertainties enters the new year under the 
cloud of the clean air act of 1990 which could devastate the 
nations highsulfur mines at first and mean trouble for all mines 
later 
its going to hurt some people its going to shift the market 
maybe and we dont know how said david branand director of 
environmental affairs for the national coal association 
overall unfortunately in the longterm i believe the clean 
air act is going to be negative for the coal industry in general 
basically because of caps or restrictions on emissions said gary 
white president of the west virginia coal association 
the clean air act which became law nov 15 restricts sulfur 
dioxide emissions from coalfired power plants considered the 
leading cause of acid rain 
those plants primarily in the midwest and ohio valley must cut 
sulfur dioxide emissions by half or 9 million tons annually in 
the next decade 
the restrictions which take effect in 1995 and tighten in 2000 
essentially give power plants that now burn highsulfur coal three 
options 
they can install scrubbers at a cost of up to 100 million 
each which would eliminate up to 90 percent of the sulfur 
emissions and allow them to continue burning highsulfur coal 
they can switch to lowersulfur coal and pay generally higher 
transportation costs 
or they can trade or sell pollution allowances permitting some 
plants to exceed standards to the extent other plants come in under 
the limits 
so much of it depends on what the utilities are going to do 
and theyre in a state of uncertainty branand said nonetheless 
utility officials must decide soon which route they will take 
if youre talking about installing scrubbers not only are you 
talking about a major financial investment youre talking about a 
major construction effort to get them installed white said 
west virginia presents a microcosm of the challenges the clean 
air act poses for the coal industry 
the states highsulfur northern coal fields stand to lose 
business because of pollution restrictions 
at the same time the states lowsulfur southern coal fields 
are getting ready for a boom 
white said he hopes for expansion in the southern coal fields 
and a minimum loss in the northern mines but hes more pessimistic 
about the industrys longterm health primarily because the law 
will make it to expensive to build ne coalfired power plants 
the key to meeting the new clean air standards lies in the 
sulfur content of coal and its ability to produce energy rated in 
british thermal units or btu said john randolph director of the 
virginia center for coal and energy research 
wyoming kentucky and west virginia produce more than half the 
nations coal coal with a sulfur content of 06 percent or less 
makes up 44 percent of the known reserves in wyoming 16 percent in 
kentucky and 37 percent in west virginia 
but the coal in kentucky and west virginia generally is more 
efficient than that in wyoming randolph said 
the average central appalachian coal produces 12500 btu per 
pound while wyoming coal can produce as little as 10000 btu per 
pound 
by 1995 power plants must limit sulfur dioxide emissions to 25 
pounds per million btu central appalachian coal with about 16 
percent sulfur content will meet the new standards randolph said 
by 2000 sulfur dioxide emissions will be limited to 12 pounds 
per million btu so central appalachian coal would have to have a 
sulfur content of 075 percent or less he said 
in both cases western coal would have to be lower in sulfur 
content to make up for the shortfall in btu 
but while the western coal is less efficient than appalachian 
coal and costs more to transport to the midwestern power plants 
that need it it also is cheaper to produce industry experts said 
in the past year huntingtonbased ashland coal inc has spent 
180 million to buy two companies with major lowsulfur reserves 
mingo logan coal co in southern west virginia and pikeville 
kybased coal mac inc 
we believe ashland coal is going to be benefited from the 
clean air act amendments said vice president david todd we feel 
optimistic about that 
quantifying that is where the uncertainty is 
