<TEXT>
howto guides are wildly popular in teaching 
everything from dating to dressing in japan where pressures to 
conform can be immense 
howto magazines attract japanese readers who are always 
fearful of doing something different by showing a standard of what 
people should be doing said masayoshi kinjo editor of the 
popular mens magazine brutus 
recently brutus described the right way to behave on a 
date 
order a tea immediately when your date shows up at a coffee 
shop to meet you smile even at waitresses and passersby to 
better your image dont order drinks that make you look like a 
wimp and finally enjoy sex 
many young japanese have trouble developing close relationships 
because of scholastic rivalries with other students and their 
parents long working hours books and television teach them how to 
do so said yasuo ueda an associate professor of journalism at 
sofia university in tokyo 
store shelves are filled with howto magazines paperbacks 
comic books and videotapes 
a typical company handbook provides guidance for conduct on the 
job 
shave every morning and clip your nails occasionally keep 
shoe polish and a brush in your locker to make your shoes always 
shiny bend your head 15 to 30 degrees when you bow but bow as 
much as 45 degrees to apologize 
researchers say reliance on such material results from an 
education system designed to make everyone the same through rules 
that dictate for instance the color of underwear and when 
students may go to the bathroom 
critics of the propensity for conformity acknowledge the 
education systems role in helping japan become an economic 
powerhouse but fault schools for failing to teach students 
creativity 
being always told what to do people stop thinking and 
young people have become very passive said ueda 
there should be so many different ways for them to live their 
own lives but people are making decisions based on a few 
stereotypes he said in an interview 
bunchin katsura a wellknown storyteller who teaches sociology 
at kansai university in osaka has had enough of the manuals 
could somebody please write a howto book entitled how not to 
depend on howto books he said 
young people like the manuals because following them provides 
reassurance that they are not outcasts from society 
katsura said the degree of reliance on selfhelp publications 
became clear to him on christmas of 1989 when he saw dozens of 
young men lined up at a hotel checkout counter while their 
girlfriends waited patiently to the side 
he attributed the lobby gridlockto magazines that instruct 
young men to seal a relationship with the opposite sex with a 
proposal to spend an intimate christmas eve in a hotel room in 
japan christmas is celebrated as an occasion to give gifts and to 
be with friends not as a religious holiday 
about 1800 howto magazines are published in japan each year 
in addition to many books according to the research institute for 
publications 
