<TEXT>
the more things have changed on wall street from 
the 80s into the early 90s the more one thing remains the same 
big stocks keep soundly thrashing smaller counterparts in the 
battle for investors favor 
as the bearmarket year of 1990 draws to a close the typical 
loss suffered by bigname blue chips is far smaller than the 
declines sustained by the great mass of smaller secondary 
stocks 
for the latest 12month period through early december the 
composite index of the new york stock exchange where most large 
stocks are traded dropped 66 percent 
over the same span both the nasdaq composite index for the 
overthecounter market and the american stock exchange market 
value index showed losses exceeding 18 percent 
this sort of thing has been happening regularly ever since the 
mid1980s in apparent contravention of a prized doctrine among 
stock analysts and academic researchers known as the small firm 
effect 
over most extended periods of time their studies have 
concluded little stocks are likely to fare better than big stocks 
if only because small companies have room for greater percentage 
growth 
several theories have been advanced to explain why this pattern 
is no longer holding for one thing big stocks got greater benefit 
from the takeover mania of the 80s than did those of small 
companies which had fewer assets to restructure 
for another big stocks had a special attraction for foreign 
investors given their familiar names and their perceived 
stability 
but the most compelling reason of all may be the longrunning 
trend toward index investing constructing portfolios for pension 
funds mutual funds and other large pools of money to look as much 
as possible like a market index such as standard amp poors composite 
of 500 stocks 
indexers mostly buy big stocks and hold them since big stocks 
dominate the makeup of the indexes they try to replicate 
indexing enjoys great popularity as a lowcost way to 
participate in longterm market gains without the risk of 
underperforming that befalls many managed stock portfolios 
it is not so popular in the stock brokerage business however 
since it downplays just about every service wall street has to 
sell from stockpicking to execution of buy and sell orders 
indeed john j phelan jr who retires dec 31 as chairman of 
the new york stock exchange cites it as a prime force in the 
recession gripping the securities industry 
it has put an enormous cost squeeze all through the system 
he said during an interview last week right from the 
moneymanagement end of it to the execution end of it 
phelans view of the nearterm future offers little consolation 
for either brokers or partisans of the small stocks indexing is 
going to continue to have an enormous influence in the market for 
the next three to five years he says 
but sooner or later he maintains the pendulum that has been 
swinging away from active money management toward indexing will 
reach a point where it turns back the other way 
just about the time everybody indexes and everybody says money 
managers cant do better than the market then were going to get a 
whole crop of them doing better than the market he said you 
know thats going to come but we havent gone to that extreme yet 
money management is the only business in the world that says 
were mediocre phelan concluded the human condition is not 
going to live with that for very long 
