<TEXT>
ten years after a flood of lowcost imports 
devastated americas steelmakers one of the nations historic core 
industries is competitive again 
it took a great deal of pain and suffering but the industry 
is now awake and in some cases remarkably astute and smart said 
john jacobson an analyst with aus consultants in philadelphia 
the pain came in the form of 200000 job reductions hundreds of 
mill closings and billions of dollars in spending to increase 
efficiency the gain is evident in falling imports and rising 
profits 
lower production costs and a weaker dollar have boosted american 
steels competitiveness us steelmakers now produce a ton of 
steel in about 5 manhours lowest in the world and nearly half 
the time it took in 1980 
still the united states remains the worlds biggest steel 
importer foreign rivals especially japan and the european 
community arent standing still 
the japanese already were further ahead and theyre running at 
a much faster pace said hans mueller an economics professor and 
consultant at middle tennessee state university the americans 
are just catching up 
in the first nine months of 1990 imports comprised about 17 
percent of the us steel market making america the worlds 
largest importer according to the american iron and steel 
institute a washington trade group most imports came from europe 
and japan followed by canada south korea brazil and many other 
countries 
the ec and japan are the worlds leading exporters of finished 
steel the united states exported about 46 million tons in 1989 
far less than the top exporters 
the relative value of international currencies more than 
anything else will determine the global competitiveness of 
american steel in the 1990s said charles a bradford a metals 
expert for union bank of switzerland in new york 
the steel industry may be the biggest beneficiary of the 
weakness in the dollar he said the biggest cost of an 
integrated steelmaker is wages if you compare wages around the 
world its all a matter of the value of the dollar 
the united states was the dominant force in the international 
steel market following world war ii and led the world in steel 
production in the 1950s 
but japan and european countries rebuilt their postwar 
industries from scratch using modern technology as us mills 
rusted imports cracked 15 percent by the 1970s and reached an 
alltime high of 264 percent in 1984 
american steelmakers lost about 119 billion from 1980 to 1986 
when hundreds of mills closed and more than 200000 workers 
nationwide left the payrolls 
the picture is brighter now steelmakers made about 15 billion 
in profits in 1989 the cost of halting production while plants 
were modernized was a major factor in 1989 and will continue to 
hurt profits 
the cost of modernization is taking its toll but in the long 
run theyre much better off bradford said this is what you 
need to do if you want to be competitive 
in 1980 about 20 percent of american steel was made in modern 
continuous casters which turn molten steel directly into slabs 
skipping costly and timeconsuming steps 
today about 66 percent of american steel is made that way and 
the figure is expected to reach about 90 percent by the year 2000 
said sheldon wesson a spokesman for the american iron and steel 
institute in 1989 japan made about 94 percent of its steel and 
belgium about 91 percent in continuous casters 
the effort goes on nobody is satisfied wesson said the 
industry says it has spent in the last 10 years perhaps half what 
it would have liked to spend on mill modernization 
you look at the profit picture and you wonder where the next 
billion is going to come from he said this is all 
selffinanced this is all pulling yourself up by the boot 
straps 
