<TEXT>
the campaign to try to brighten up wall street 
in time for the holidays has received some extra lastminute help 
from the federal reserve 
but analysts warn that a promise of cheaper money from the fed 
and its chairman alan greenspan by itself is no assurance of a 
cheery start on the new year 
the central bank acted last tuesday afternoon to lower the 
discount rate the charge it sets on loans to private financial 
institutions to 65 percent from 7 percent where it had stood for 
almost two years 
the cut did not come as a total surprise to the investment 
world but most analysts who had been talking about the possibility 
were projecting it for some time after jan 1 
thus the timing as much as the substance of the move was 
interpreted as a signal that the fed was stepping up the pace of 
its efforts to ease credit conditions and relieve the pressures of 
a developing recession 
among the tools at the feds disposal the discount rate is 
often described as powerful symbolic and psychological device but 
observers are quick to add that it is not a magic wand 
in the midst of the last sustained bear market for stocks the 
fed also sent a message of christmas cheer to investors cutting 
the discount rate from 14 percent to 12 percent on dec 4 1981 
it was not until the second half of 1982 however that stocks 
bottomed out and the economy began its recovery from recession 
in todays situation furthermore many analysts wonder if 
cutting the price of money will be enough to get it moving faster 
through the financial system 
were in a credit crunch all right but it is not being 
engineered by the federal reserve board asserts charles 
laloggia a rochester ny investment adviser 
the credit crunch stems from the fact that the banking system 
is awash in bad loans which are getting worse by the day both 
bankers and banking regulators are now scared stiff of making new 
loans 
a credit contraction as described by james grant in his 
grants interest rate observer newsletter is a kind of malady 
unseen since the 1930s 
in a credit contraction he says borrowers are denied 
the principal rationing device for loans is not high interest rates 
but low creditworthiness the credit of the borrower or the 
liquidity of the lending institution or both 
such misgivings helped to mute the celebration in the financial 
world that followed the feds announcement at fridays close the 
dow jones average of 30 industrials stood at 263366 up 3985 
points from the week before 
the new york stock exchange composite index rose 216 to 18087 
the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter market gained 
478 to 37361 and the american stock exchange market value index 
was u 046 at 30620 
volume on the big board averaged 17670 million shares a day 
against 15585 million the week before 
as if to dispel any illusions that the fed could dictate the 
level of interest rates bond traders pushed rates on longterm 
government bonds higher as the week progressed 
bond traders keep a continuous antiinflation watch manifesting 
their concern every time the fed takes a step toward stimulus that 
they suspect might eventually increase inflationary pressures 
at the moment however most forecasters dont see inflation as 
a major menace to the markets any time soon 
inflation should prove to be much less of a problem in 1991 
than it has been in recent years contends david blitzer 
economist at standard amp poors corp 
we expect to see some of the smallest price increases since 
the mid1980s and have hopes that the gains against inflation will 
be longlasting ones 
