<DOCNO> AP901221-0193 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when it began welfare in northern 
europe was meant to stop the destitute from becoming a public 
nuisance todays welfare states regard a fair income as a 
universal right 
the 8thcentury emperor charlemagne decreed that his nobility 
should distribute food to poor peasants to keep them from joining 
marauding bands of beggars 
europe always has known institutionalized charity usually under 
religious auspices but elements of the modern welfare state 
appeared only a little over a century ago when cities were clogged 
with working families 
mechanization and poor working conditions created the need for 
health and accident insurance while economic downturns created a 
jobless class less easily absorbed than in farming society 
chancellor otto von bismarck gave germany a compulsory health 
insurance plan in 1883 similar programs followed there in the next 
few years for industrial injury disability and old age 
norways first state insurance law which provided accidental 
injury coverage for all was passed in 1894 followed by laws in 
1906 on medical insurance for the poor and oldage pensions in 
1936 
in the depressionridden 1930s sweden and the netherlands set 
up loosely defined social welfare programs modeled on the new deal 
of president franklin d roosevelt 
the dutch program quickly became so essential that a minor cut 
in benefits sparked three days of street riots in amsterdam in 
which five were killed 
cradletograve welfare programs were advocated by scandinavias 
dominant leftwing political parties after world war ii 
everyone has the right to employment a place to live 
education social security and health and hospital systems the 
result is a society in which there are few truly rich or poor 
says a book on social welfare published by oslos aftenposten 
newspaper 
a late arrival on the welfare scene is finland a largely 
agrarian nation where rural societies carried out their own 
informal welfare functions 
it was not until 1957 that finland passed its first major 
welfare law the national pensions act its comprehensive 
unemployment benefits law was not voted through until 1985 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901221-0194 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
welfare state benefits can be so 
lucrative that even the recent offer of cars for personal use 
wasnt enough to lure dutch unemployed off the dole 
welfare recipients in denmark and the netherlands are frequently 
entitled to subsidies that help pay their rent child care basic 
furnishings and clothes 
coming on top of cash benefits those addons often mean a 
welfare recipient has a bigger income than a skilled industrial 
worker 
