moscow mikhail s gorbachev will be challenged in 1991 as he 
seeks to prevent the further economic and political collapse of the 
soviet union 
gorbachevs international prestige remains high as demonstrated 
by the nobel peace prize awarded him in october and his continuing 
summits with western leaders 
at home however few soviet citizens have reason to celebrate 
the traditional new year holiday store shelves are often bare in 
major cities and many consumer items are scarce throughout the 
country 
although he has helped reduce world tension by concluding arms 
agreements pulling back from eastern europe and withdrawing the 
soviet army from afghanistan gorbachev has balked at the jump from 
a planned to a market economy many western analysts say that is 
essential to boosting production 
six years after gorbachev began relaxing 70 years of strict 
communist party controls ethnic unrest continues conservatives 
have urged tougher measures to curb it 
gorbachev prefers a more moderate course a new union treaty 
that would hold the 15 soviet republics together as a federation 
rather than under central control but some republics refuse to 
take part in the talks and others oppose his plan to keep economic 
control in the central governments hands 
the baltic republics of lithuania latvia and estonia have 
declared independence and moldavia shows signs of following suit 
armenia is boycotting the talks because the kremlin will not give 
it control of the disputed nagarnokarabakh region 
russia by far the largest republic wants to sell its abundant 
oil natural gas diamond and gold for dollars on the world market 
rather than to the central governmnt for rubles as gorbachev 
proposes some other republics are following russias lead 
 
