<TEXT>
in a quest to sweeten profits the nations 
banks are holding off as long as possible before they cut their 
prime lending rate 
the normal rush among banks to follow a move in the prime rate 
didnt develop after first national bank of chicago cut its prime 
05 percentage point to 9 thursday morning 
in healthier times the nations largest banks such as citibank 
and chase manhattan generally would have followed first national 
the nations 13th largest banking company by cutting their prime 
rates as well economists said but banks are holding out as long 
as possible to profit from the difference in their borrowing costs 
and the interest borrowers pay them 
first chicagos move came one day after the federal reserve cut 
the discount rate its loan fee to financial institutions by 05 
percentage point to 6 percent in order to stimulate the economy 
through looser credit it was the first cut in that key rate since 
august 1986 
banks are suffering through the worst earnings crunch in many 
years and in some cases are experiencing higher funding costs 
despite the feds actions said fritz elmendorf spokesman for 
the consumer bankers association in arlington va 
a cut in the prime is watched closely because bankers use it as 
a basis for calculating loans to businesses and for determining 
many types of fixed and adjustablerate consumer loans the prime 
rate reflects a banks costs of borrowing money including interest 
it pays on savings accounts or certificates of deposit 
though bankers deny theyre profiting at consumers expense 
economist howard sharpe disagreed 
yes consumers are being gouged but the problem is that if 
the banks dont stay solvent the consumer would get gouged even 
more said sharpe chief economist of sharpes capital market 
associates inc in new york 
federal bank regulators are pressuring banks to improve their 
equity capital ratios which help cushion a bank from failure the 
federal deposit insurance corp predicts 180 banks with total 
assets of 70 billion will fail next year because of declining real 
estate values and a souring economy 
a number of banks are expected to improve capital levels by 
slashing dividends this quarter in the face of rising loan losses 
a delay in a prime rate cut can slightly boost profits and make 
things a little better for the grim quarter 
a decision to delay a prime rate cut has very little to do 
with raising capital said sharpe 
bankers say the cost of their funds still remains high despite 
the feds actions the fed has cut the federal funds rate the rate 
banks charge each other on overnight loans three times this month 
to 7 percent 
the question is why hasnt the funds rate come down because 
people are scared they dont know which bank will be in trouble 
sharpe said 
samuel d kahan chief economist for fuji securities inc said 
the reason why bank costs havent declined is that banks must still 
pay relatively high rates of interest to holders of 3month 
certificats of deposit one of the banking industrys major 
sources of funds 
although there is an appearance that rates have gone down 
they have not come down for banks he said the prime rate is 
set to move in line with the cost of bank funds 
earlier this month a handful of smaller banks cut their prime 
rates to 9 percent in response to more subtle fed policies to 
encourage lending 
the national bank of canada and canadian imperial bank both cut 
their prime rates 05 percentage point to 12 percent on thursday 
which banking analysts called an indirect result of american 
lending policies 
