<TEXT>
clarence l kelly johnson creator of 
lockheed corps secret skunk works aircraft factory and a leading 
designer of the u2 and sr71 blackbird spyplanes died today at 
age 80 
a lockheed statement said johnson died at st joseph medical 
center after an illness of many years but did not disclose the 
illness 
johnson organized the skunk works in 1943 to build the xp80 
shooting star the united states first production jet fighter 
many aircraft and spacecraft bore his mark the p38 lightning 
in world war ii the constellation transports the hercules cargo 
planes the p2v antisubmarine patrol aircraft and the agena 
spacecraft among others 
other designs on which he played a major role included the f104 
starfighter the first production aircraft to fly at twice the 
speed of sound the u2 the first plane able to make a sustained 
flight above 60000 feet and the yf12 and sr71 blackbird the 
worlds fastest and highestflying planes 
the blackbirds recently retired by the air force could fly 
more than 2000 mph and for long durations above 85000 feet 
johnson born in ishpeming mich on feb 27 1910 went to 
work for lockheed as a tool designer in 1933 he went on to head 
the skunk works for 30 years 
he retired as a corporate senior vice president in 1975 and 
retired from lockheeds board of directors in 1980 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

