<TEXT>
the european community friday voted to 
continue compensating the united states for reduced corn exports 
into spain and portugal avoiding a costly transatlantic trade war 
washington had been gearing up to increase duties on several ec 
food and drink products if the ec had decided to end compensations 
for losses in corn and sorghum exports to spain and portugal 
the united states will now refrain from such measures and resume 
negotiations with the community to settle the issue for good by the 
end of next year officials said 
the temporary settlement ended one of three farm disputes that 
have been marring trade relations between the united states and the 
12member ec the move was also expected to facilitate attempts to 
restart the world trade talks that collapsed earlier this month 
the talks supervised by the general agreement on tariffs and 
trade fell apart over farm subsidies that the united states wants 
to eliminate but the ec hopes to maintain 
the talks are scheduled to resume in geneva next month 
the corn dispute arose after spain and portugal joined the trade 
bloc in 1986 and import duties were increased on us corn and 
sorghum feedgrains 
one year later the ec trade bloc agreed to compensate the 
united states for losing an estimated 400 million in annual trade 
two million tons of corn and 300000 tons of sorghum now are 
allowed into spain and portugal under reduced levies 
the ec wanted to end the compensations this year but granted a 
oneyear extension friday after the the united states threatened to 
retaliate with about 400 million in extra duties on ec products 
the ec and the united states are still at odds over two other 
issues one is the banning of us pork imports for what the ec 
considers to be unsanitary slaughterhouse conditions in the united 
states 
the other is a us ban on ec sparkling wines that contain a 
japanese additive which washington thinks could be unhealthy 
</TEXT>
