<TEXT>
if lower interest rates from the federal reserve 
are going to rescue the economy the central bank needs help from 
consumers banks and businesses 
the banks seem to be starting to go along 
first national bank of chicago the nations 13thlargest us 
banking company was the first major lender to follow the feds 
lead lowering its prime rate from 10 percent to 95 percent 
smaller banks also moved to ease their prime rates as well 
interest rates on many business and consumer loans like home 
equity lines of credit are tied to the prime 
lower borrowing costs for consumers combined with optimism that 
the recession might be short lived could prompt many to buy a new 
car dishwasher or even a new house 
slouching consumer confidence has been one of the darkest clouds 
hanging over this recession 
in november the conference board a businesssupported research 
group reported its consumer confidence index fell near levels last 
seen in the depths of the 1982 recession 
the conference boards survey found more people expecting higher 
unemployment and weaker business conditions in the coming months 
and were scaling back plans for major purchases 
businesses have also started to change their plans based on 
economic pessimism the commerce department reported last week that 
businesses planned to increase spending to modernize by a scant 04 
percent in 1991 
this year modernization spending increased 41 percent 
there are a lot of different ways you send a message 
lowering the fed funds rate is a very technical message the 
discount rate is still another way of communicating and the fed was 
trying to do something dramatic but the prime rate is very visible 
to a lot of people said maury harris chief economist at 
painewebber inc 
fluctuations in the discount rate interest the fed charges to 
lend money to banks have little direct affect on the economy and 
the move to lower the rate from 7 percent to 65 percent was seen 
widely as symbolic 
in an economy driven by perceptions symbols are important 
the feds message was clear and sent loudly announced in the 
afternoonon on an otherwise slow news day many editors at 
newspapers and broadcasting stations treated the move as the days 
top story rather than a purely business news development 
recent moves by the fed to lower the federal funds rate 
interest banks charge each other for overnight loans to 7 percent 
have been largely left to the business pages 
the fed wanted to tell consumers they are going to do 
something the message to banks was think about lowering 
interest rates said brian j fabbri chief economist at midland 
montagu a division of midland bank 
the message to everyone was that the fed has made the recession 
its top priority rather than the antiinflation tight money 
policy 
this summers tightmoney policy which was intended to bring 
the economy into a soft landing to squeeze out inflation was 
blown off course when saddam hussein invaded kuwait aug 2 
the invasion and higher oil prices which took money out of 
consumers pockets on top of the tight money policy pushed the 
economy into recession fabbri said 
although lower interest rates may help pull the economy around 
they may not hold the quick answer fabbri said 
it will take six to 12 months for increased borrowing and 
increased bank profitability to lead the way to recovery he said 
