could contain 25 billion barrels of oil that would be enough to 
supply all the american oil needs for decades 
the uncertainties facing the oil giants were heightened this 
week when soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze quit 
shocking president mikhail s gorbachev and stirring concerns that 
a dictatorship could emerge or that more troubles could develop 
it could be a detriment exxon spokesman lance lamberton 
said i cant quantify it 
the soviet union is the worlds largest oil producer but its 
industry has fallen on hard times after peaking out at 125 million 
barrels of crude oil a day in 1988 
its now down to 113 lichtblau said the general 
assumption is that it will continue to decline to under 10 million 
barrels a day in couple of years thats a huge decline if nothing 
is done it could go down to nine perhaps 
the problem is technology the soviets have extracted much of 
the oil that was relatively easy to obtain and they are unable to 
get to some additional reserves which will bring in needed hard 
currency without help from the west 
big oil companies looking toward the soviet union can envision 
the potential for vast production possibly even enough to cut back 
on the market clout wielded by the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries 
the uncertainties of dealing with the soviets are obvious but 
the recent persian gulf crisis shows that the west already depends 
on an uncertain energy supply several potentially unstable sources 
of energy are logically better than only one strategists say 
theyre not likely to be unavailable at the same time since 
their politics are totally different lichtblau said 
its unclear how much new oil could be found in the soviet 
union although some experts say higher production could easily 
equal that of a moderatesized opec member 
for now efforts by us companies involve enhanced production 
of crude that has already been discovered rather than 
wildcatting or looking for new oil fields 
in one such venture a private company synergy trading corp 
of greenwich conn hopes to set up a deal worth at least 250 
million for enhancing onshore wells in the soviet republic of 
azerbaijan and a deal worth more than 1 billion for developing 
new offshore wells there 
william f wilson who handles equity crude deals for synergy 
estimated the onshore project could produce 15 to 20 million 
barrels of oil a year 
offshore could be double that wilson said friday 
it remains uncertain how much of the oil synergy and its 
partners could obtain the soviets will not let western companies 
get involved in existing production but they have expressed a 
willingness to let oil companies claim a portion of new oil they 
can produce 
synergys executives who have years of experience in making 
grain and oil deals with the soviets said they can get approval 
for the onshore project from azerbaijan authorities while the 
offshore deal needs to be cleared by soviet authorities in moscow 
synergy said political troubles in the soviet union and its 
republics can slow things but the executives dont believe it will 
stop any deals 
youve just got a longer fuse in these projects wilson 
said 
</TEXT>
