<DOCNO> AP901221-0240 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
american companies that still do business in 
south africa find that economic sanctions havent hurt their 
business performance new investment research findings show 
since 1980 companies with south african business ties saw their 
return on investment improve by one percentage point per year over 
companies without business dealings in that nation researcher john 
freeman said in an interview friday 
return on investment a commonly used barometer to measure a 
companys financial performance is a percentage calculated by 
dividing assets into net income 
the joint research by freeman a manager for barra an 
investment consulting firm in berkeley calif and martingdale 
asset management in boston sought to neutralize all the other 
things and isolate the south african factor freeman said 
their unpublished research was conducted for investment fund 
managers to help them understand the risk of divestiture from south 
africa he said 
the study showed that between january 1980 and august 1984 
companies with south african ties lost 150 basis points in the 
return on investment annually when compared with nonsouth african 
companies a basis point is onehundredth of a percentage point 
the trend then reversed itself from august 1984 to october 
1990 companies with south african ties outperformed the others by 
280 basis points per year 
freeman admitted the research results surprised him activists 
who oppose apartheid south africas policy of racial separation 
were surprised as well 
the research raises the question of whether the sanctions were 
designed to make companies unattractive as investments hurt their 
business or merely force them out of south africa 
our view is the goal was to get major companies to leave south 
africa said patrick mcveigh vice president of franklin research 
and development corp in boston franklin offers what it calls 
socially responsible investment portfolios for companies without 
south african connections 
he said wounding a companys performance generally was a 
secondary weapon of divestment but it never was a primary 
goal 
since 1984 170 us companies have removed their employees or 
direct investments in south africa said meg vorhees south african 
research director at the investor responsibility research center in 
washington which keeps track of american corporate relations with 
south africa she said 114 us companies maintain direct 
investments or employees in that nation 
the pullout stems from international outrage over the political 
suppression and human rights abuses of south africas blacks as of 
june 1990 19 states and 55 cities have adopted policies calling 
for full or partial divestiture of securities with south african 
links said ms vorhees 
the divestment question was posed to numerous government pension 
funds endowments and foundations throughout the 1980s scattered 
protests flared on college campuses during the period as students 
urged school pull south africanrelated investments 
she criticized the martingdalebarra findings saying most 
american companies derive a small amount of their business from 
south african subsidiaries or investments 
its hard for me to believe it would make that much of a 
difference in general us companies with operations in south 
africa account for less than 1 percent of their assets she said 
franklin says its south africaclean investment portfolio has 
performed slightly better than the standard and poors 500 index 
during a 15year period the difference is very small said 
mcveigh if anything over time its become less of an issue 
because of the companies that have pulled out of south africa 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

