<TEXT>
former dallas thrift president edwin t mcbirney 
iii agreed to plead guilty to fraud and help federal investigators 
chase other thrift scandal figures the justice department said 
friday 
mcbirney who led sunbelt savings association is the second 
major thrift official in two days to be convicted of wrongdoing 
that cost taxpayers millions of dollars 
a federal court jury on thursday found former vernon savings 
association owner don r dixon guilty of 23 counts of fraud and 
misapplication of funds a magistrate ordered dixon held without 
bond until his feb 19 sentencing 
federal prosecutors have dealt a onetwo punch to the savings 
and loan crooks this week attorney general dick thornburgh said 
in washington 
sunbelts 1986 failure is estimated to have cost taxpayers 2 
billion and vernons in 1987 cost 13 billion 
in return for his help prosecutors agreed to limit mcbirneys 
penalty to 75 million in restitution and 85 million to settle 
civil claims by the federal deposit insurance corp mcbirney also 
may be sentenced to up to 15 years imprisonment 
we are confident that mr mcbirneys cooperation is going to 
lead to the indictment of other major insiders in the next two 
years said marvin collins us attorney for the northern 
district of texas 
mcbirney 37 filed the plea in federal court friday a date had 
not been scheduled for him to appear before a judge 
the deal was made last month but prosecutors arranged not to 
file or publicize it until dixons trial was over collins said 
they did not want to risk complicating the dixon trial which 
began in october he said in september the fraud conviction of 
two vernon borrowers was thrown out when the judge learned the jury 
had discussed dixons indictment during its deliberations 
we were being perhaps just a little extra cautious collins 
said with these very large cases we are taking extra care 
mcbirney who was indicted in july on 17 counts agreed to plead 
guilty to four counts of bank fraud filing a false corporate tax 
return causing a false statement to be filed by sunbelt and 
misapplying 250000 in sunbelt funds 
the bank fraud count stems from a 700 million deal to finance 
the purchase of real estate in southern california by a sunbelt 
subsidiary 
mcbirney agreed to admit that he arranged a fraudulent 30 
million reciprocal loan arrangement with western savings 
association another former dallas thrift to help finance the real 
estate deal 
the former owner of western savings jarrett woods goes on 
trial next month on 37 charges he misapplied funds and falsified 
records that led to the thrifts 1 billion failure 
dixon 52 was convicted of illegally spending money from his 
vernon savings association on prostitutes and a california beach 
house he could be sentenced to as many as 115 years in prison and 
fined 575 million for his convictions on 23 fraud counts 
