<TEXT>
the fbi arrested three men friday in an 
alleged 2 millionamonth scheme to lease nonexistent copy 
machines to businesses around the country 
the fbi said in an affidavit that the defendants purported to 
sell the copiers to companies that buy used xerox corp machines 
for leasing 
the buyers believed the copiers would be leased for them by a 
pennsylvania company the fbi said the alleged scam relied on the 
buyers never having to see the machines since they supposedly were 
being leased by a third party 
this is a typical pyramid scheme where an investor group pays 
in a large amount and is then paid back on a monthly basis milt 
ahlerich the fbis special agent in charge of connecticut said 
they think they are getting a terrific return on their 
investment but the money is actually coming out of their original 
investment he said 
randy t hilgert 32 of madison thomas j becker of north 
kingstown ri and john f rodgers of arcola pa each was 
charged with wire fraud mail fraud and money laundering ahlerich 
said 
hilgert was released friday on 25000 bond the status of the 
other two men was not known federal agents seized property 
belonging to the three and records from the businesses involved 
the alleged victim companies were paid a monthly fee for leasing 
the nonexistent machines sales of the machines averaged about 2 
million a month but in september for example lease payments 
totaled only 570000 
a large percentage of the victims were banks located around the 
country ahlerich said several companies allegedly were victimized 
but declined to specify 
hilgert was the broker for the machines the fbi said he 
allegedly deposited about 500000 a week into an account at the 
new england savings bank in madison the bank which said it knew 
hilgert for years as a local carpenter and landscaper notified the 
fbi about the deposits 
on the same day he made the deposits the fbi said hilgert 
would wire 90 percent of the money to becker associates of 
bridgeport pa 
in one example hilgert sold 14 used copiers to banc one leasing 
corp of columbus ohio which believed the machines would be 
leased by becker associates which was operating under the name 
rhino copy the affidavit said 
rhino copy was supposed to be leasing the machines for banc one 
and then making monthly payments to the bank the fbi said since 
it was receiving monthly payments on time banc one decided to buy 
10 more machines 
fbi special agent marilyn lucht went to pennsylvania for banc 
one to inspect the machines the company thought it owned the 
affidavit said she found about 90 copiers at rhino copy but only 
six were operational 
lucht said becker and rodgers told her all of their machines 
were leased had been purchased by hilgert and were refurbished by 
centralized services inc 
centralized services was a vendor and refurbisher of the used 
copiers sold by hilgert to the victim leasing companies fbi said 
lucht said in an affidavit that the company only exists on 
paper 
centralized services president is a former xerox repairman 
ralph sylvestri the fbi said he has not been charged and the fbi 
declined to comment on his role in the investigation 
</TEXT>
